<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
    <title>Use cases - bughq</title>
    <meta name="description" content="How frontend, backend, mobile, on-call, and agency teams put bughq error tracking to work in production.">
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com">
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Space+Grotesk:wght@400;500;600;700&family=JetBrains+Mono:wght@400;500;600&display=swap">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/marketing.css">
  </head>
  <body>
    @include('SiteNav')

    <main>
      <nav class="subnav shell" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a><span class="sep">/</span>
        <span>Use cases</span>
      </nav>

      <section class="feat-hero shell">
        <span class="kicker">Use cases</span>
        <h1>A net under every team that ships to production.</h1>
        <p>The same SDK and the same triage fit a browser bundle, a background worker, or a native app. Here is how different teams lean on bughq, and which features do the work.</p>
        <div class="hero-actions">
          <a class="btn primary" href="/register">Get started</a>
          <a class="btn ghost" href="/docs">Read the docs</a>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section shell reveal" aria-label="Use cases">
        <div class="usecases">

          <article class="usecase">
            <img src="https://picsum.photos/seed/bughq-frontend-browser/720/340" alt="A web application open in a browser" width="720" height="340" loading="lazy">
            <div class="usecase-body">
              <h3>Frontend</h3>
              <p>Catch the errors your users actually hit in the browser. Upload a source map and every minified frame resolves back to the component and line that threw.</p>
              <a class="textlink" href="/use-cases/frontend">How teams use bughq for frontend</a>
            </div>
          </article>

          <article class="usecase">
            <img src="https://picsum.photos/seed/bughq-backend-api/720/340" alt="Server and API infrastructure" width="720" height="340" loading="lazy">
            <div class="usecase-body">
              <h3>Backend</h3>
              <p>Server, edge, and job failures arrive with the request, release, and environment attached, so a 500 names the route and the deploy that broke it.</p>
              <a class="textlink" href="/use-cases/backend">How teams use bughq for backend</a>
            </div>
          </article>

          <article class="usecase">
            <img src="https://picsum.photos/seed/bughq-mobile-app/720/340" alt="A mobile app on a phone" width="720" height="340" loading="lazy">
            <div class="usecase-body">
              <h3>Mobile</h3>
              <p>Native crashes and JavaScript errors fold into one issue per build, so you see which release regressed and how many devices it reached.</p>
              <a class="textlink" href="/use-cases/mobile">How teams use bughq for mobile</a>
            </div>
          </article>

          <article class="usecase">
            <img src="https://picsum.photos/seed/bughq-oncall-sre/720/340" alt="An on-call engineer reviewing alerts" width="720" height="340" loading="lazy">
            <div class="usecase-body">
              <h3>On-call and SRE</h3>
              <p>Alerts fire for new and spiking issues, not for every known warning. Triage by release and affected-user count instead of scrolling a raw log.</p>
              <a class="textlink" href="/use-cases/on-call">How on-call teams use bughq</a>
            </div>
          </article>

          <article class="usecase">
            <img src="https://picsum.photos/seed/bughq-agency-clients/720/340" alt="Multiple client projects on a board" width="720" height="340" loading="lazy">
            <div class="usecase-body">
              <h3>Agencies</h3>
              <p>Keep each client site as its own project with its own issues, releases, and members, so you know exactly which build on which site started erroring.</p>
              <a class="textlink" href="/use-cases/agencies">How agencies use bughq</a>
            </div>
          </article>

        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section shell reveal" aria-label="Get started">
        <div class="cta-band">
          <h2>Ship with a net under you.</h2>
          <div class="cta-actions">
            <a class="btn primary" href="/register">Get started</a>
            <a class="btn ghost" href="/docs">Read the docs</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>

    @include('SiteFooter')
  </body>
</html>
